an ethnographic study of the state as viewed from its margins. It starts from the premise that the seeming "margin" of state administration is not peripheral at all, but instructive as to how it functions. As Elise Massicard shows, muhtars exist at the intersection of everyday life and the exercise of power. Their position offers a personalized point of contact between citizens and state institutions, enabling close oversight of the citizenry, yet simultaneously projecting the sense of an accessible state to individuals. Challenging common theories of the state, Massicard outlines how the position of the muhtar throws into question an assumed dichotomy between domination and social resistance, and suggests that considerations of circumvention and accommodation are normal attributes of state-society functioning.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisacsh  aIstanbul.  aNeighborhood.  aTurkey.  aanthropology of state.  aeveryday politics.  ainformal politics.  alocal politics.  astreet-level.  aurban politics.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503631861423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503631861/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles